t beliefs, cultural practices, mythologies and cosmologies. Details: The opening takes place on December 8 at the Johannesburg Art Gallery, corner Klein and King George Streets, Joubert Park. Entry is free. For more information call 011 725 3130 Abantu Book Festival: Founded to promote black literature across the continent, the festival is now in its fourth year. This year those who attend will have the opportunity to be addressed by the likes of Buhle Ngaba, Zakes Mda, Chike Frankie Edozien, Chris Abani, and Lebo Mashile. Details: The festival is taking place until December 8. Day events are held at the Eyethu Lifestyle centre, 00651 Tshabalala Street, Mofolo Central, Soweto, 1801. Entry is free. Night sessions take place at the Soweto Theatre, corner Bolani Link and Bolani Road, Jabulani, Soweto, 1868. Entry at night sessions cost R20 at the door. For more information visit their website. Mind Yoga: Be The Shift offers a secular program focusing on a release of stress and anxiety through various exercises and activities, none of which involve breaking a sweat. With no need for a mat or previous experience, all you need to bring is an open mind and a desire to know stillness. Details: The program takes place on December 8 at Suncoast Casino, Suncoast Boulevard, O R Tambo Parade Durban. Entry is free. For more information visit their website or call 031 328 3000. Poetry Church: Brought to you by the department of sports, arts, culture and recreation, this performance unpacks the corruption of the church and the effect it has on the communities surrounding the religious entities. Details: The show takes place on December 7 and 8 at the South African State Theatre, 320 Pretorius Street, Pretoria Central, Pretoria. Tickets cost R100 and can be purchased from Webtickets. For more information visit the State Theatre’s website. Burning At the Stake: Unlike the festival performances that patrons may have seen of Msaki, the artist has curated this live experience to fit the intimate feel of the venue. Details: The show will take place on December 11 and 12 at the Untitled Basement, 7 Reserve Street, Braamfontein. Tickets cost R200 and can be purchased from Quicket. For more information call 011 339 1647 . Frozen Fun Slide Park: The whole family gets to enjoy the summer at this Frozen themed fun park. The park contains an Olaf play area and a number of other slides. This entertainment is in anticipation for the debut of Frozen 2 on Friday, 6 December. Details: The park is currently open until January 5 at the Canal Walk Shopping Centre, Century Boulevard, Milnerton, Cape Town. tickets cost between R35 to R100 and can be purchased from Webtickets. For more information visit Canal Walk’s website or call 021 529 9699. Festive Evening Market: This market is bringing a farm charm into the hustle and bustle of the capital city. Details: The market will be held on December 8 at the Centurion Farm Stall Market, corner of Lyttleton Road and Fairway Avenue, Clubview, Centurion. Entry is free. For more information visit their website